# Scenario: per-request allocation is flat in the CYCLE pool across request
# SIZE, not just request count -- and across every size CLASS of allocation.
#
# WHAT THIS ADDS OVER soak-delta. scenarios/soak-delta asserts `delta
# pool.cycle_used == 0` across ten batches -- but every one of its requests is
# the same tiny `GET /`, and it watches only ONE of the three cycle-pool
# counters. That leaves two gaps this scenario closes:
#
#   1. SIZE of request. A long request line spills into a
#      large_client_header_buffer; large header values allocate several of
#      them; a request body walks ngx_http_discard_request_body. Those paths
#      run only when a request is BIG and never for a tiny soak. They size
#      their buffers in the REQUEST pool, freed wholesale at request end, so a
#      correct server leaves the cycle pool flat no matter how large the
#      request was -- but a module that copies request-sized data somewhere
#      longer-lived leaks in proportion, invisibly to a tiny-request soak.
#
#   2. SIZE class of allocation. The probe exposes three cycle-pool counters
#      and a leak surfaces most loudly in a DIFFERENT one depending on how big
#      each leaked block is (src/ngx_test_probe.c:142). ngx_palloc splits at
#      NGX_MAX_ALLOC_FROM_POOL (pagesize-1, ~4 KiB): a smaller block is carved
#      from the pool's block chain and its full size lands in `cycle_used`; a
#      larger block is a separate malloc hung off pool->large, so its bytes
#      never reach `cycle_used` -- only the ~16-byte ngx_pool_large_t node
#      does (the large list stores pointers, not sizes; the loop at :168 counts
#      nodes). A per-request large leak therefore drifts `cycle_used` by a
#      barely-visible 16 B while `cycle_large` climbs by a clean +1 -- so a
#      scenario watching only `cycle_used`, as soak-delta does, sees a 16 B/req
#      trickle where the direct count sees the leak plainly. Asserting all
#      three counters means a per-request leak of ANY size class reds on the
#      counter it moves most, and the diagnostic names the size class.
#
# WHY pool.* AND NOT the request pool. Request pools are freed at request end
# (ngx_http_free_request), so a delta across them is always zero -- vacuous.
# The cycle pool lives for the life of the worker; nothing in normal request
# handling may allocate there. It is the one arena where a per-request leak
# accumulates.
#
# WHY delta==0 AND probe_baseline==0, NOT an absolute figure. The absolute
# counters depend on the build (nginx vs angie), the version and the conf
# (these generous header-buffer limits pre-size structures at config parse), so
# they are NOT portable -- cycle_used measured 67287 on one conf, 67364 on
# this one. The defect this hunts is GROWTH, which the relative operators see:
# `delta` localises a jump to the case that caused it, `probe_baseline` (fixed
# origin, README "Catching a slow leak") bounds the cumulative drift a
# constant-per-request leak hides from every per-case delta. Both are exactly
# zero on a healthy server -- the cycle pool was measured dead flat across
# every request size below.
#
# WHY LARGE HEADER VALUES, NOT MANY HEADER LINES. The size here comes from a
# few long headers, not thousands of short ones: angie caps the header-line
# COUNT ("client sent too many header lines" -> 400) where nginx bounds only by
# buffer bytes, so a many-lines block nginx accepts angie rejects before the
# probe ever runs. Two ~48 KiB values span the same buffers with a handful of
# lines and reach the handler (200) on both.
#
# NON-VACUITY (proven locally against nginx 1.29.0; restore the .so after).
#   - A SMALL leak: flip the reference module's response-buffer alloc from
#     r->pool to ngx_cycle->pool (ngx_http_test_ref_module.c:160). Each request
#     leaks a JSON-sized (~3 KiB, sub-pagesize) block into the block chain ->
#     every `delta cycle_used` reds (+3040/req) and the closing baseline reds.
#   - A LARGE leak: ngx_palloc(ngx_cycle->pool, 100000) per request. The 100 KB
#     is a large alloc, so `cycle_used` drifts only ~16 B/req (the large-list
#     node) while `delta cycle_large` reds by +1/req -- a signal soak-delta's
#     cycle_used-only check would see as noise, and the reason this scenario
#     watches all three counters. (The case still reds either way; the settle
#     loop prints the first failing delta, which for this leak is cycle_used's
#     node-overhead drift.)

name    baseline: a tiny request
send    GET /__probe HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=200
probe   fds >= 1
probe   pool.cycle_used >= 1
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0
delta   pool.cycle_blocks == 0
delta   pool.cycle_large == 0

# A long request line: ~30 KiB of query string. nginx parses it into the first
# large_client_header_buffer -- a request-pool allocation that scales with the
# line length and is freed at request end.
name    a 30 KiB request line
send    GET /__probe?
repeat  480 pad=aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa&
send     x=1 HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=200
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0
delta   pool.cycle_blocks == 0
delta   pool.cycle_large == 0

# Two ~48 KiB header values, spanning several large_client_header_buffers with
# only a handful of lines. This is the path that only runs for big requests and
# never for soak-delta's tiny ones.
name    a ~96 KiB header block (two long values)
send    GET /__probe HTTP/1.1\r\nX-Pad-1:
repeat  800 aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa
send    \r\nX-Pad-2:
repeat  800 bbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbb
send    \r\nHost: prober\r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=200
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0
delta   pool.cycle_blocks == 0
delta   pool.cycle_large == 0

# The same again, back to back: a leak proportional to header size would have
# doubled the cycle pool by now; a constant-per-request leak would have added
# two units the per-case deltas cannot see but the closing baseline can.
name    the ~96 KiB header block again
send    GET /__probe HTTP/1.1\r\nX-Pad-1:
repeat  800 aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa
send    \r\nX-Pad-2:
repeat  800 bbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbb
send    \r\nHost: prober\r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=200
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0
delta   pool.cycle_blocks == 0
delta   pool.cycle_large == 0

# A 256 KiB request body the handler discards (ngx_http_discard_request_body,
# ngx_http_test_ref_module.c:133). The read path allocates client-body buffers
# in the request pool; a module that stashed the body elsewhere leaks here.
name    a 256 KiB discarded body
send    GET /__probe HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\nContent-Length: 262144\r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
repeat  4096 aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa
expect  status=200
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0
delta   pool.cycle_blocks == 0
delta   pool.cycle_large == 0

# The closing case returns to a tiny request and carries the cumulative bounds.
# probe_baseline subtracts from the origin read before case 1, so a constant
# per-request leak that every per-case delta above absorbed lands here. Exactly
# zero on all three counters because the cycle pool was measured dead flat
# across every size above.
name    tiny again, cumulative bound
send    GET /__probe HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=200
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0
delta   pool.cycle_blocks == 0
delta   pool.cycle_large == 0
probe_baseline fds <= 2
probe_baseline pool.cycle_used == 0
probe_baseline pool.cycle_blocks == 0
probe_baseline pool.cycle_large == 0
